Strings and text blocks.

The string class is the most used class in Java. Strings are immutable. Every operation that looks like it modifies a string actually returns a new string. The variable greeting holds the string hello. If you call greeting dot to upper case, you get back a new string, hello in capital letters, and the original greeting variable still points to the lower case hello. Concatenation uses the plus operator. The String dot format method gives you printf style formatting. And since Java fifteen, the string class also has a dot formatted instance method that lets you write a format string followed by dot formatted, with the arguments in parentheses.

For multi line strings, Java fifteen added text blocks. A text block is a triple quoted string literal that preserves newlines and indentation rules. Triple quote, newline, content, triple quote. Text blocks are the cleanest way to embed JSON, structured query language, or HTML inside Java code. The compiler strips a common leading whitespace prefix from every line of the block, using the position of the closing triple quote as the baseline. This means you can indent the literal to match the surrounding code without that extra indentation appearing in the resulting string.
